      <hedline>
        <hl1>Librarians as Web Guides</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from librarian David Ettinger suggests checking with librarian before wasting time on futile Web searches (Feb 5 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''When a Search Engine Isn't Enough, Call a Librarian'' (Feb. 5), highlighting the important role librarians play assisting patrons lost in the information wilderness of the Internet age:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''When a Search Engine Isn't Enough, Call a Librarian'' (Feb. 5), highlighting the important role librarians play assisting patrons lost in the information wilderness of the Internet age:</p>
        <p>Seduced by the prospect of immediate gratification, it is no wonder why so many people turn to Web search engines. Frustrated, savvy information seekers may want to reverse your prescription: check with a librarian first before wasting countless hours surfing the Web.</p>
        <p>David Ettinger  Washington</p>
        <p>The writer is a reference librarian at Gelman Library at George Washington University.</p>
      </block>
